ce:section.ce:para:
Herein, this paper mainly focuses on realizing the CDs-based afterglow materials with dual emission centers and tunable excitation-dependent RTP and TADF properties by combining Cu, N co-doping and matrix-assisted methods, which opens up a new way for advanced anti-counterfeiting and encryption. Moreover, the afterglow enhancement and tuning mechanism are revealed. Using boric acid (BA) as the matrix, the negative electronegativity of boron atoms is utilized to promote the formation of p-π conjugated systems and reduce the ΔE
                     ST between the single and triplet states. The oxidized glassy rigid matrix of BA could protect the excited triplet states. Moreover, the afterglow is enhanced by the interaction between oxygen vacancy electron defects of matrix and electrons of CDs. First, dual-emission Cu, N-CDs with afterglow emission potential were synthesized by solvothermal method. Subsequently, Cu, N-CDs were embedded into a rigid matrix to obtain the tunable RTP and TADF afterglow composite material (Cu, N-CDs@BA) through the electron transfer enhancing afterglow. Cu, N-CDs@BA can realize the mutual conversion of RTP and TADF by simply changing the excitation wavelength or increasing temperature. Finally, Cu, N-CDs@BA can be applied to the anti-counterfeiting icon drawing and information encryption coding owing to their three different emission modes (FL, RTP, and TADF), which exhibits good application potential (Scheme 1
                     ).
